Open /etc/hosts on your client machine and **remove** or comment out the lines mapping www.priyam.com.
```bash
sudo vi /etc/hosts
# Remove these lines:
# 127.0.0.1       www.priyam.com
# 192.168.74.74   www.priyam.com

```
## 2. Install and Configure BIND9 (On your DNS Server)
If your DNS server is running on the same machine or a separate server (let's assume your server IP is 192.168.74.74), install BIND9:
```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt install bind9 bind9utils bind9-doc -y

```
### Step A: Define the Zones in named.conf.local
Open the local configuration file to declare your Forward and Reverse zones:
```bash
sudo vi /etc/bind/named.conf.local

```
Add the following zone definitions:
```text
// Forward Lookup Zone
zone "priyam.com" {
    type master;
    file "/etc/bind/db.priyam.com";
};

// Reverse Lookup Zone (Based on network 192.168.74.x)
zone "74.168.192.in-addr.arpa" {
    type master;
    file "/etc/bind/db.192";
};

```
## 3. Create the Zone Data Files
### Step B: Create the Forward Zone File (db.priyam.com)
Create a new file by copying the default local template:
```bash
sudo cp /etc/bind/db.local /etc/bind/db.priyam.com
sudo vi /etc/bind/db.priyam.com

```
Configure it with your **A (Address) records** and **CNAME (Alias) records**:
```text
;
; BIND forward zone file for priyam.com
;
$TTL    604800
@       IN      SOA     ns1.priyam.com. root.priyam.com. (
                              2         ; Serial
                         604800         ; Refresh
                          86400         ; Retry
                        2419200         ; Expire
                         604800 )       ; Negative Cache TTL
;
; Name Servers
@       IN      NS      ns1.priyam.com.

; IP Addresses for Hostnames
ns1     IN      A       192.168.74.74
@       IN      A       192.168.74.74
www     IN      A       192.168.74.74

```
### Step C: Create the Reverse Zone File (db.192)
This handles the **PTR (Pointer) records**, which allows entities to verify that your IP explicitly maps back to your domain name (crucial for security compliance and auditing).
```bash
sudo cp /etc/bind/db.127 /etc/bind/db.192
sudo vi /etc/bind/db.192

```
Configure it like this (note that 74 at the bottom corresponds to the last octet of 192.168.74.74):
```text
;
; BIND reverse zone file for 192.168.74.x
;
$TTL    604800
@       IN      SOA     ns1.priyam.com. root.priyam.com. (
                              1         ; Serial
                         604800         ; Refresh
                          86400         ; Retry
                        2419200         ; Expire
                         604800 )       ; Negative Cache TTL
;
; Name Servers
@       IN      NS      ns1.priyam.com.

; PTR Records (Mapping IP last octet to FQDN)
74      IN      PTR     www.priyam.com.
74      IN      PTR     ns1.priyam.com.

```
## 4. Verify and Restart DNS Service
Before starting the service, always check your syntax to make sure there are no typos that could crash the daemon:
```bash
# Check global configurations
sudo named-checkconf

# Check zone file syntax
sudo named-checkzone priyam.com /etc/bind/db.priyam.com
sudo named-checkzone 74.168.192.in-addr.arpa /etc/bind/db.192

# If everything says OK, restart BIND
sudo systemctl restart bind9

```
## 5. Configure the Client to Use Your New DNS
Your client machine (or browser host) needs to know where to find this new DNS server. Edit the network resolver configuration file:
```bash
sudo vi /etc/resolv.conf

```
Add your DNS server IP at the very top:
```text
nameserver 192.168.74.74

```
## 6. Testing the Setup (Verification)
To verify that network resolution is behaving exactly like your original layout, execute these diagnostic commands on your client machine:
```bash
# Test Forward Resolution (Should return 192.168.74.74)
nslookup www.priyam.com

# Test Reverse PTR Resolution (Should return www.priyam.com)
nslookup 192.168.74.74

```
Once nslookup returns the correct values, open Firefox and navigate to https://www.priyam.com. The browser will transparently query your BIND server, obtain the IP, initialize the TLS handshake with Apache, cross-verify the certificate with the imported rootCA.crt, and securely serve your webpage with a valid HTTPS padlock indicator.
